03449nam a22005895i 9780823296507DE-B159720220524034747.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220524t20222004nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808232965077 a10.1515/97808232965072doi  a(DE-B1597)626424  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aPHI0020002bisacsh1 aSorrell, Kory Spencer, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aRepresentative Practices :bPeirce, Pragmatism, and Feminist Epistemology /cKory Spencer Sorrell. 1aNew York, NY : bFordham University Press, c[2022] 4c©2004  a1 online resource (228 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aAmerican Philosophy00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAbbreviations -- tForeword -- tINTRODUCTION -- tONE. PEIRCE'S CATEGORIES A First Glimpse at Representation -- tTWO. THE SUBSTANCE OF PEIRCE'S CATEGORIES The World Phenomenologically Conceived -- tTHREE. MAPPING THE PROVINCE From the Mirror of Nature to Constructive Representation -- tFOUR. COMMUNITIES OF INQUIRY Authority, Constraint, and Inclusivity -- tFIVE. MEDIATION AND NORMATIVE SCIENCE Toward an Ethic of Representation -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAlthough widely recognized as founder and key figure in the current re-emergence of pragmatism, Charles Peirce is rarely brought into contemporary dialogue. In this book, Kory Sorrell shows that Peirce has much to offer contemporary debate and deepens the value of Peirce’s view of representation in light of feminist epistemology, philosophy of science, and cultural anthropology. Drawing also on William James and John Dewey, Sorrell identifies ways in which bias, authority, and purpose are ineluctable constituents of shared representation. He nevertheless defends Peirce’s realistic account of representation, showing how the independently real world both constrains social representation and informs its content. Most importantly, Sorrell shows how members of a given community not only represent but transform a shared world—and how those practices of representation may, and should, be improved.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 7aPHILOSOPHY / History & Surveys / Ancient & Classical.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978082329650740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780823296507423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780823296507/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK